[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837667426370&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837667426370&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

It seems amazingly clear to me that UUCP is only one of several
"store-and-forward" relay style networks that have internal needs for
the use of conventions that are different from those that apply in a
DDN style Internet where-in every host is able to establish direct
IP/TCP transfers with every other host in the net.

So, if we are to take seriously the "decentralized naming authority"
idea, then I believe we need to let the subdomains deal with their
problems as they see fit, as long as they do not interfere with other
sub/super domains by their actions.  What is wrong with UUCP acting as
a coherent whole subdomain if its inmates like it that way?

Of course, this does not disallow some sites from using uucp software
and being interconnected with the internet, without being in UUCP, per
se.  As long as they do not violate DoD rules as stated by Mark,
everything should be OK.  There is no apparent rule forcing anyone to
join UUCP.

Stef

